<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:George_Cruikshank_-_Tristram_=
Shandy,_Plate_V._My_Uncle_Toby_on_his_Hobby-horse.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-des=
cription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/=
3/3a/George_Cruikshank_-_Tristram_Shandy%2C_Plate_V._My_Uncle_Toby_on_his_H=
obby-horse.jpg/250px-George_Cruikshank_-_Tristram_Shandy%2C_Plate_V._My_Unc=
le_Toby_on_his_Hobby-horse.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"=
319" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"3984" data-file-height=3D=
"5080"></a><figcaption>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tristram=
_Shandy" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Tristram Shandy">Tristram Shandy</a=
>, the term "hobby-horse" was used to refer to whimsical obsessions, which =
led to the current use of the word "hobby". </figcaption></figure>
<p>A <b>hobby</b> is considered to be a regular activity that is done for e=
njoyment, typically during one's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/L=
eisure_time" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Leisure time">leisure time</a>.=
 Hobbies include <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collecting" title=
=3D"Collecting">collecting</a> themed items and objects, engaging in creati=
ve and artistic pursuits, playing <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Sport" title=3D"Sport">sports</a>, or pursuing other amusements or <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Avocation" title=3D"Avocation">avocations=
</a>. Participation in hobbies encourages acquiring substantial skills and =
knowledge in that area. A list of hobbies changes with renewed interests an=
d developing fashions, making it diverse and lengthy. Hobbies tend to follo=
w trends in society. For example, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Stamp_collecting" title=3D"Stamp collecting">stamp collecting</a> was popul=
ar during the nineteenth and twentieth centuries as postal systems were the=
 main means of communication; as of 2024<sup class=3D"plainlinks noexcerpt =
noprint asof-tag update" style=3D"display:none;"><a class=3D"external text"=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DHobby&amp;action=3Ded=
it">[update]</a></sup>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Video_game=
s" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Video games">video games</a> became more =
popular following technological advances. The advancing production, technol=
ogy, and labour movements of the nineteenth century provided workers with m=
ore leisure time to engage in hobbies. Because of this, the efforts of peop=
le investing in hobbies has increased with time.
</p><p>There are various <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobby#Typ=
es_of_hobbies">types of hobbies</a>, which can be classified in various way=
s, including subject matter, degree of time commitment, and social versus s=
olitary nature. The Serious Leisure Perspective of <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Stebbins_(academic)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D=
"Robert Stebbins (academic)">Robert Stebbins</a> identifies hobbies under t=
hree sub-categories: <i>casual leisure,</i> which is intrinsically rewardin=
g, short-lived, pleasurable activity requiring little or no preparation; <i=
>serious leisure,</i> which is the systematic pursuit of an amateur, hobbyi=
st, or volunteer that is substantial, rewarding and results in a sense of a=
ccomplishment; and finally <i>project-based leisure,</i> which is a short-t=
erm, often one-off, project that is rewarding.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:1_1-0" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobby#cite_note=
-:1-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup>
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Etymology">Etymology</h2><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DHobby&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Etymology"><span>edit</span=
></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In the 16th century, the term "hobby" had the meaning of "small horse an=
d pony". The term "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobby_horse_(to=
y)" title=3D"Hobby horse (toy)">hobby horse</a>" was documented in a 1557 p=
ayment confirmation for a "Hobbyhorse" from Reading, England.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobby=
#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> The item, originally called a "Tourney Horse", was=
 made of a wooden or basketwork frame with an artificial tail and head. It =
was designed for a child to mimic riding a real <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Horses_in_the_Middle_Ages#Types_of_horse" title=3D"Horses in =
the Middle Ages">horse</a>. By 1816 the <a href=3D"https://en.wiktionary.or=
g/wiki/derivative" class=3D"extiw" title=3D"wikt:derivative">derivative</a>=
, "hobby", was introduced into the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Vocabulary" title=3D"Vocabulary">vocabulary</a> of a number of English peo=
ple.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Hobby#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Over the course of subsequent ce=
nturies, the term came to be associated with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Recreation" title=3D"Recreation">recreation</a> and <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leisure" title=3D"Leisure">leisure</a>. In the=
 17th century, the term was used in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Pejorative" title=3D"Pejorative">pejorative</a> sense by suggesting tha=
t a hobby was a childish pursuit, however, in the 18th century with more in=
dustrial society and more leisure time, hobbies took on greater respectabil=
ity.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Gelber_S_M_1999,_p._12_4-0" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobby#cite_note-Gelber_S_M_1999,_p._1=
2-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> A hobby is also called a <b>pastime</b>, derived from the u=
se of hobbies to <i>pass the time</i>. A hobby became an activity that is p=
racticed regularly and usually with some worthwhile purpose.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-Gelber_S_M_1999,_p._12_4-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobby#cite_note-Gelber_S_M_1999,_p._12-4"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Hob=
bies are usually, but not always, practiced primarily for interest and enjo=
yment, rather than financial reward.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DHobby&amp;action=3Dedi=
t&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</span></a><sp=
an class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Prior to the mid-19th century, hobbies were generally considered as an o=
bsession, childish or trivial, with negative connotations.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-:2_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hob=
by#cite_note-:2-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> However, as early as 1676 Sir Matthew Hale, i=
n <i>Contemplations Moral and Divine</i>, wrote "Almost every person hath s=
ome hobby horse or other wherein he prides himself."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Hal=
e1676_6-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hob=
by#cite_note-Hale1676-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> He was acknowledging that a "hobby hor=
se" produces a legitimate sense of pride. The cultural shift towards accept=
ance of hobbies was thought to begin during the mid 18th century as working=
 people had more regular hours of work and greater leisure time, spending m=
ore time to pursue interests that brought them satisfaction.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-Gelber_S_M_1999,_p._12_4-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobby#cite_note-Gelber_S_M_1999,_p._12-4"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> How=
ever, there was concern that these working people might not use their leisu=
re time in worthwhile pursuits. "The hope of weaning people away from bad h=
abits by the provision of counter-attractions came to the fore in the 1830s=
, and has rarely waned since. Initially, the bad habits were perceived to b=
e of a sensual and physical nature, and the counter attractions, or perhaps=
 more accurately alternatives, deliberately cultivated rationality and the =
intellect."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobby#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The book and magazine tra=
de of the day encouraged worthwhile hobbies and pursuits. The burgeoning ma=
nufacturing trade made materials used in hobbies cheap and was responsive t=
o the changing interests of hobbyists.
</p><p>In 1941, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Orwell" tit=
le=3D"George Orwell">George Orwell</a> identified hobbies as central to Eng=
lish culture at the time: "Another English characteristic which is so much =
a part of us that we barely notice it =E2=80=A6 is the addiction to hobbies=
 and spare-time occupations, the <i>privateness</i> of English life. We are=
 a nation of flower-lovers, but also a nation of stamp-collectors, pigeon-f=
anciers, amateur carpenters, coupon-snippers, darts-players, crossword-puzz=
le fans. All the culture that is most truly native centers round things whi=
ch even when they are communal are not official=E2=80=94the pub, the footba=
ll match, the back garden, the fireside and the 'nice cup of tea'."<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Hobby#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Deciding what to include in a list of hobbies provokes debate becaus=
e it is difficult to decide which pleasurable pass-times can also be descri=
bed as hobbies. During the 20th century the term hobby suggested activities=
, such as stamp collecting, embroidery, knitting, painting, woodwork, and p=
hotography. Typically the description did not include activities like liste=
ning to music, watching television, or reading. These latter activities bri=
ng pleasure, but lack the sense of achievement usually associated with a ho=
bby. They are usually not structured, organized pursuits, as most hobbies a=
re. The pleasure of a hobby is usually associated with making something of =
value or achieving something of value. "Such leisure is socially valorized =
precisely because it produces feelings of satisfaction with something that =
looks very much like work but that is done of its own sake."<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-Gelber_S_M_1999,_p._12_4-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobby#cite_note-Gelber_S_M_1999,_p._12-4"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> "Ho=
bbies are a contradiction: they take work and turn it into leisure, and tak=
e leisure and turn it into work."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Gelber_S_M_1999,_p._12=
_4-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobby#ci=
te_note-Gelber_S_M_1999,_p._12-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A 2018 study using survey resu=
lts identified the term "hobby" to most accurately describe activities asso=
ciated with making or collecting objects, especially when done alone.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-:2_5-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Hobby#cite_note-:2-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Cultural trends related to hobbies change with time. In the 21st cen=
tury, the video game industry has been popular as a hobby involving million=
s of children and adults. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stamp_co=
llecting" title=3D"Stamp collecting">Stamp collecting</a> declined along wi=
th the importance of the postal system. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Woodwork" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Woodwork">Woodwork</a> and <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Knitting" title=3D"Knitting">knitti=
ng</a> declined as hobbies, because manufactured goods provide cheap altern=
atives for handmade goods. Through the internet, an <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Online_community" title=3D"Online community">online commu=
nity</a> has become a hobby for many people; sharing advice, information an=
d support, and in some cases, allowing a traditional hobby, such as <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collecting" title=3D"Collecting">collecti=
ng</a>, to flourish and support trading in a new environment.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobby=
#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Hobbyists">Hobbyists</h2><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DHobby&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Hobbyists"><span>edit</span=
></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Hobbyists are a part of a wider group of people engaged in <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leisure#Types_of_leisure" title=3D"Leisure">lei=
sure</a> pursuits where the boundaries of each group overlap to some extent=
. The <i>Serious Leisure Perspective</i><sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_10-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobby#cite_note-:0-=
10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> groups hobbyists with amateurs and volunteers and identifie=
s three broad groups of leisure activity with hobbies being found mainly in=
 the Serious leisure category. <i>Casual leisure</i> is intrinsically rewar=
ding, short-lived, pleasurable activity requiring little or no preparation.=
 <i>Serious leisure</i> is the systematic pursuit of an amateur, hobbyist, =
or volunteer that is substantial, rewarding and results in a sense of accom=
plishment. Finally, <i>project-based leisure</i> is a short-term often a on=
e-off project that is rewarding.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:1_1-1" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobby#cite_note-:1-1"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up>
</p><p>The terms amateur and hobbyist are often used interchangeably. Stebb=
ins<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_10-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Hobby#cite_note-:0-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> has a framework which =
distinguishes the terms in a useful categorization of leisure in which <i>c=
asual leisure</i> is separated from <i>serious Leisure</i>. He describes se=
rious leisure as undertaken by <i>amateurs</i>, <i>hobbyists</i> and <i>vol=
unteers</i>. <i>Amateurs</i> engage in pursuits that have a professional co=
unterpart, such as playing an instrument or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Astronomy" title=3D"Astronomy">astronomy</a>. Hobbyists engage in=
 five broad types of activity: <i>collecting</i>, <i>making and tinkering</=
i> (like embroidery and car restoration), <i>activity participation</i> (li=
ke fishing and singing), <i>sports and games</i>, and <i>liberal-arts</i> h=
obbies (like languages, cuisine, literature). Volunteers commit to organiza=
tions where they work as guides, counsellors, gardeners and so on. The sepa=
ration of the amateur from the hobbyist is because the amateur has the etho=
s of the professional practitioner as a guide to practice. An amateur clari=
netist is conscious of the role and procedures of a professional clarinetis=
t.
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Girls_und_Panzer_Triumph.jpg" class=3D"mw-fil=
e-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/t=
humb/7/73/Girls_und_Panzer_Triumph.jpg/250px-Girls_und_Panzer_Triumph.jpg" =
decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"194" class=3D"mw-file-element" d=
ata-file-width=3D"3867" data-file-height=3D"3000"></a><figcaption>There are=
 people who enjoy motorcycle touring alone or in groups, and there are also=
 club teams.</figcaption></figure>
<p>A large proportion of hobbies are mainly solitary in nature.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-Gelber_S_M_1999,_p._12_4-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobby#cite_note-Gelber_S_M_1999,_p._12-4"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><=
sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page / location: 28">:=E2=80=
=8A28=E2=80=8A</span></sup> However, individual pursuit of a hobby often in=
cludes club memberships, organized sharing of products and regular communic=
ation between participants. For many hobbies there is an important role in =
being in touch with fellow hobbyists. Some hobbies are of communal nature, =
like choral singing and volunteering.
</p><p>People who engage in hobbies have an interest in and time to pursue =
them. Children have been an important group of hobbyists because they are e=
nthusiastic for collecting, making and exploring, in addition to this they =
have the leisure time that allows them to pursue those hobbies. The growth =
in hobbies occurred during industrialization which gave workers set time fo=
r leisure. During the Depression there was an increase in the participation=
 in hobbies because the unemployed had the time and a desire to be purposef=
ully occupied.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hobby#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Hobbies are often p=
ursued with an increased interest by retired people because they have the t=
ime and seek the intellectual and physical stimulation a hobby provides.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Types_of_hobbies">Types of =
hobbies</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DHobb=
y&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Types of hobbie=
s"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></sp=
an></div><p>
 Hobbies are a diverse set of activities and it is difficult to categorize =
them in a logical manner. The following categorization of hobbies was devel=
